<td class="article-body"><DIV class=newsHead><STRONG>Safin Outlasts No. 4 Nalbandian in Marathon</STRONG></DIV>
<P>by Neil Schlecht<BR><I>Sunday, September 3, 2006</I></P>
<P><IMG height=400 src="/Admin/spaw/DatabaseImages/USO0647.jpg" width=280 border=0></P>
<P><BR></P>
<P>You kind of knew this one would go the distance.</P>
<P>Not to be outdone by the emotional drama of Andre Agassi’s final match next door on Arthur Ashe Stadium, David Nalbandian and Marat Safin traded the first two pairs of sets on a sun-baked afternoon and went toe-to-toe until a tension-filled fifth-set tiebreak decided the outcome. After nearly four hours, Safin outlasted Nalbandian, 6-3, 7-5, 2-6, 3-6, 7-6 (6). </P>
<P>David Nalbandian, an Argentine who’s normally rock-steady, rarely makes things easy for himself. But the same could be said for his opponent, Marat Safin, a Russian whose talent is only equaled by his frustrating ability to squander it. </P>
<P>Nalbandian is a grinder who seems to enjoy long, drawn-out encounters, while Safin appears to need the drama. Coming into this matchup, Nalbandian, one of only three active players to have reached the semifinals at all four Grand Slam events, had won four matches after coming back from a two sets-to-one deficit. </P>
<P>Safin, the former US Open and Australian Open champion, has plummeted outside the Top 100, so his victory over a slumping Nalbandian, the No. 4 seed who had won only one hard-court match leading up to the US Open, was technically an upset. Safin, though, owns Nalbandian in career head-to-head meetings, 6-1.</P>
<P>In the very first game of the first set, Safin immediately challenged a line call on the baseline and then disagreed demonstratively with the Instant Replay, which showed the ball clearly on the line. As if playing on clay, the Russian banged his racket on a spot where he thought the ball fell. Nonetheless, Safin held it together, broke serve at 3-4 and served out the set, 6-3.</P>
<P>The second set was delayed by nearly 15 minutes as a fan who had collapsed courtside was revived, given oxygen and helped out in a wheelchair. Safin did not let the break in play disturb his rhythm, and though his first cry of anguish came after missing a forehand wide at 2-3, he used his massive, 130-mph-plus serve to ward off trouble. </P>
<P>Nalbandian’s faltering confidence was evident early on, as he made uncharacteristic errors on routine forehands. Through the first three sets, there was little rhythm to the match, as both players struggled with their consistency. </P>
<P>At 5-5 in the second, Safin smashed his racket to the court with a loud splat, then turned around and played a sublime point to get back to deuce. After the outburst, the Russian broke serve and then held to take the set. </P>
<P>Nalbandian rebounded in the third set, breaking Safin twice to push the match into a fourth set with a 6-2 win. The Argentine also rolled in the next , 6-3, forcing a fifth set</P>
<P>In the final set, both players steadied their games and did a much better job of defending their serves. The tiebreak began and ended peculiarly. Safin began by double-faulting, but Nalbandian handed the advantage right back by throwing in his own double. On the next point, the Russian hit a return of serve that dribbled over the net cord for a winner. </P>
<P>Safin nearly blew a commanding 5-1 lead in the tiebreak, allowing Nalbandian back into it with yet another double fault. On match point, Safin, out of position, stretched wide for a stab forehand from deep in his corner. The ball barely skimmed the net and Nalbandian, looking to drop it short in the court, instead dumped the shot softly into the net. </P>
<P>Safin is a mercurial personality with Top 2 talent and a 104 ranking. As he demonstrated over the course of this long match, he is capable of giving opponents, fans and himself fits with his up-and-down play. When he is on, his game—an effortless display of power and precision—is sublime. But it can be maddenly uninspired when his concentration and patience wane. </P>
<P>In a quest to return to his expected place among the sport’s elites, the 6-foot-5 Safin next meets Olivier Rochus of Belgium, who at 5-foot-4 has won their last two matches. </P><BR clear=left>
